# Build Configuration - Unreal Engine 5.7

## Build.cs Files
- Defines project module dependencies
- Use `PublicDependencyModuleNames` for modules used in public headers
- Use `PrivateDependencyModuleNames` for modules used only in .cpp
- Keep minimal dependencies for faster builds
- Add only what is necessary

## Common Modules
- **Core, CoreUObject, Engine** - Always included (basic)
- **InputCore, EnhancedInput** - For input
- **UMG, Slate, SlateCore** - For UI
- **GameplayTasks** - For async tasks
- **AIModule** - For AI
- **OnlineSubsystem** - For online features

## Optimized Build.cs Example
```csharp
public class MyProject2 : ModuleRules
{
    public MyProject2(ReadOnlyTargetRules Target) : base(Target)
    {
        PCHUsage = PCHUsageMode.UseExplicitOrSharedPCHs;

        // Public dependencies (used in headers)
        PublicDependencyModuleNames.AddRange(new string[] {
            "Core",
            "CoreUObject",
            "Engine",
            "InputCore",
            "EnhancedInput"
        });

        // Private dependencies (used only in .cpp)
        PrivateDependencyModuleNames.AddRange(new string[] {
            // Add only what is necessary
        });
    }
}
```

## Target.cs Files
- Defines build configurations for different targets
- `MyProject2.Target.cs` - Game build
- `MyProject2Editor.Target.cs` - Editor build
- Use `ExtraModuleNames` to include custom modules

## Best Practices
- **ALWAYS** regenerate project files after modifying `.Build.cs`
- Add dependencies only when necessary
- Use `PrivateDependencyModuleNames` when possible (more efficient)
- Avoid circular dependencies between modules
- Document non-obvious dependencies
